WGAAT IS SUPER KEYWORD IN JAVA ?
ANS- The super keyword in java is a referance variable is reffer to the immediate parent class object.
It mainly used in inhertance -
1.To acess variable.
2.To acess method.
3.to acess constructor.


1.USEING SUPER TO REFER THE VARIABLE :-
When the subclass has a varable with the same name as parents class,super is used to acess the parents class variable.
class Parent {
    int num = 100;
}

class Child extends Parent {
    int num = 200;

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Child num: " + num); // 200
        System.out.println("Parent num: " + super.num); // 100
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Child obj = new Child();
        obj.display();
    }
}


2. Using super to call parent class methods
If the child class overrides a method from the parent class, you can still call the parent class version using super.methodName().
class Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal makes sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }

    void display() {
        super.sound(); // calls parent method
        sound();       // calls child method
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {                     //Animal makes sound
        Dog d = new Dog();                                      //Dog barks
        d.display();
    }
}

3. Using super to call parent class constructor

When you create a subclass object, the parent constructor is always called first.
You can explicitly call a specific parent constructor using super().

Important Rules of super
super() must be the first line in the subclass constructor if used.
You cannot use super in static methods, because super refers to an instance.
super can be used only inside a subclass.
If you don’t explicitly call super(), Java automatically inserts a default super() to call the parent’s no-arg constructor.


